  "summary": "Frances DeWinter visits Bobbie at a sanatorium, bringing lilies. Bobbie explains that he has become a sensation at the facility after surviving an overdose of eight morphine tablets. He reveals that the morphine was placed in a beer bottle, noting that the paper on the bottle's cap had not been sticking properly, suggesting someone spiked the drink while he was asleep. Analysis of the leftover beer confirmed it contained lethal amounts of the drug, though no source for the morphine was found at the bar.\n\nFrankie proposes a theory connecting Bobbie’s poisoning to a previous incident where a man named Prichard was pushed off a cliff. She argues that Bobbie was not targeted for an inheritance or revenge, but because the perpetrator believed Bobbie witnessed the crime. Frankie suggests that even if Bobbie did not see the actual push, he might have noticed a distinguishing physical feature of the killer. She further links this to a strange job offer Bobbie received from a foreign company, theorizing that the perpetrators first tried to move him overseas before attempting to kill him. Bobbie remains skeptical of the connection, noting that another person, Thomas, was present at the cliff but was not poisoned. Despite his doubts, Bobbie admits the theory makes him feel important. Frankie concludes the visit by promising to return the following day.",
